f:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Hyperliquid calculates funding rates every hour based on the 8-hour TWAP premium between the perpetual price and underlying spot index. The funding exchange occurs at the top of each hour, with rates determined by the deviation between futures and spot prices across multiple reference exchanges. Unlike traditional 8-hour funding cycles, this accelerated schedule creates more frequent arbitrage windows but requires active position management. The on-chain settlement ensures transparent rate calculation without centralized intermediaries affecting the funding mechanism."}]
10:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","BTC","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BTC/USDT represents Hyperliquid's highest volume perpetual contract, providing deep liquidity for large arbitrage positions without significant slippage. The pair's correlation with broader crypto sentiment often creates pronounced funding rate premiums during volatile periods, especially when retail traders heavily favor long positions. The 1-hour funding cycle amplifies these opportunities compared to traditional 8-hour cycles on centralized exchanges."}]]}]
11:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BTC/USDT on Hyperliquid exhibits distinct funding patterns during market cycles, with rates typically ranging from -0.05% to +0.15% per hour during normal conditions. Bull markets frequently push funding rates above +0.20% hourly as leveraged longs dominate, while bear market capitulations can drive rates deeply negative. The 1-hour cycle amplifies these movements compared to 8-hour funding, creating 24 distinct funding events daily versus 3 on traditional exchanges. Weekend periods often show reduced volatility in funding rates due to lower institutional activity, though retail-driven momentum can still create significant premiums."}]]}]
12:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Execution"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The hourly funding schedule creates systematic arbitrage opportunities against 8-hour funding exchanges, particularly during trending markets where funding premiums persist across multiple cycles. Traders can capture funding differentials by shorting BTC/USDT on Hyperliquid while longing on exchanges like Binance or OKX, collecting funding income hourly versus paying every 8 hours. The on-chain nature requires careful gas optimization and position sizing to account for blockchain settlement costs. Cross-DEX arbitrage becomes profitable when funding rate differentials exceed 0.03% per hour after accounting for transaction fees and slippage costs."}]]}]
13:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Limitations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Hyperliquid's single-chain architecture creates concentrated smart contract risk, as the entire perpetual system depends on one L1 blockchain's continued operation and security. The USDC-only settlement introduces stablecoin depeg risk that could affect position valuations during market stress. Limited cross-chain bridge options may create liquidity constraints during high-demand periods, potentially affecting arbitrage exit strategies. The exchange's newer operational history means less stress-testing during extreme market conditions compared to established CEX platforms, requiring conservative position sizing for funding rate strategies."}]]}]
14:["$","$L16",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Hyperliquid's 1-hour funding differ from traditional 8-hour cycles for BTC/USDT?","answer":"Hyperliquid's 1-hour funding creates 24 daily settlement events versus 3 on most exchanges, allowing more frequent capture of funding premiums but requiring active management. The accelerated cycle amplifies short-term funding rate movements and creates unique arbitrage windows against traditional exchanges."},{"question":"What are the gas costs for BTC/USDT funding rate arbitrage on Hyperliquid?","answer":"Hyperliquid's L1 typically charges minimal transaction fees (under $0.01 per trade), making micro-arbitrage strategies viable even for smaller position sizes. The low costs enable profitable arbitrage on funding rate differentials as small as 0.01% per hour after accounting for the 0.02% maker fees."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage BTC/USDT funding rates between Hyperliquid and centralized exchanges?","answer":"Yes, cross-platform arbitrage is possible by shorting on the exchange with higher funding rates while longing on the other. However, you must account for different funding schedules, with Hyperliquid's hourly cycle versus 8-hour cycles elsewhere creating timing complexities for position management."},{"question":"What position sizes work best for BTC/USDT funding arbitrage on Hyperliquid?","answer":"Optimal position sizes typically range from $10,000 to $500,000 in notional value to balance funding income against market impact. Larger positions may experience slippage in Hyperliquid's order book, while smaller positions may not generate sufficient funding income to justify the active management required."}]}]
